Implement the private `do_overlapping/4` function.

`do_overlapping(tree, qs, qf, acc)` walks the augmented interval tree and collects,
into the accumulator `acc`, every stored interval that overlaps the query range
`[qs, qf]`. Two intervals overlap when they share at least one point, so touching
endpoints count (`s <= qf and f >= qs`). It returns the accumulated list.

The function must use the tree's `max_finish` augmentation to prune branches so the
traversal stays efficient:

  * An empty subtree (`nil`) contributes nothing — return `acc` unchanged.
  * If a node's `max_finish` is strictly less than `qs`, then no interval anywhere in
    that subtree can reach the query range, so return `acc` unchanged without
    descending.
  * Otherwise, for a live node with interval `{s, f}`:
      - Prepend the node's own interval to `acc` when it overlaps the query, i.e. when
        `s <= qf and f >= qs`.
      - Recurse into the left subtree.
      - Because the tree is ordered by the full `{start, finish}` tuple, every interval
        in the right subtree has a start `>= s`. So only recurse into the right subtree
        when `s <= qf`; if `s > qf`, the right subtree cannot contain any overlap and is
        skipped.
      - Return the resulting accumulator.

The accumulator is threaded through the recursive calls (left, then conditionally
right) and intervals are prepended as they are found.

